ve, and especially upskill is now critical in todays job market.\r\n\r\nJobs are changing more quickly than people can meet business needs. With such rapid technological movement, the World Economic Forum (WEF) projects that half of all jobs will require a change in skill sets by 2027.\r\n\r\nThe tech industry has been struggling with a skills shortage for many years. With the increasing demand for technology professionals and a limited pool of skilled workers, companies are still looking for the right talent to meet their needs.\r\n\r\nBusinesses are still looking for professionals across the IT sector, from computer infrastructure to security, and the problem isn\'t only with developers and data scientists.\r\n\r\nAccording to a new report from analyst Gartner, businesses think that talent shortage is the most significant barrier to adopting 64% of new technologies. In most cases, IT leaders who want to deploy a new tool to boost business outcomes anticipate that the need for more suitable workers to implement the technology will be problematic at some point.\r\n\r\nSeveral things, such as a lack of diversity in the IT sector, an aging labor force, and the rapid speed of technological development, brings it on. The COVID-19 pandemic has only worsened matters because many computer firms have switched to remote employment and can hire people worldwide.\r\n\r\nEven with the end of the pandemic, businesses are now carrying over their digital transformation plans. Gartner\'s survey shows that 58% of IT leaders reported either an increase or a plan to increase emerging technology investment through 2021.\r\n\r\nUnsurprisingly, in the context of a global health crisis, much of the focus remains on improving resilience: 63% of respondents in the survey cited resilience as a primary investment driver.\r\n\r\nThe shortage of tech talent is broader than just software development and programming. There is also a need for more skilled workers in areas such as cybersecurity, data science, and artificial intelligence. This has resulted in high salaries for tech professionals and intense competition among companies for top talent.\r\n\r\nTo address the shortage of tech talent, companies are exploring several strategies, such as offering competitive salaries, exible work arrangements, and opportunities for professional development. Some are also investing in employee training and development programs and outreach programs to encourage underrepresented groups to pursue careers in technology.\r\n\r\nDue to a skills shortage, the tech industry will likely continue to face difficulties in the upcoming years. However, with the correct approaches, businesses can draw in and keep the talent they require to thrive in a market that is becoming more and more competitive.\r\n\r\nThis is where Power Learn Project under the 1milliondevs4Africa comes in.\r\n\r\nPower Learn Project is a social enterprise registered as a non-profit organization whose goal is to drive transformative change for youth in Africa by powering them with relevant Tech skills by providing quality and decentralized Tech training.\r\n\r\nOur model empowers learners to take learning as a personal responsibility. It is accomplished by curating a simple-to-follow curriculum that allows learners to move from simple to advanced concepts with the least direction possible.\r\n\r\nUnderstanding that one of the best ways to learn is by teaching someone a concept learned. This has allowed us to ensure peer collaboration is at the forefront of our learning model. It has allowed our learners to unite, share knowledge, support each other, and collaborate on projects beyond PLP.\r\n\r\nWe don\'t just train, but we train to ensure our learners have a tangible impact on the tech space and society at large. To achieve this, our model places real-world skills at the center of our learning. Before our learners graduate, they must conceptualize, design and implement a solution that addresses a real-world problem.\r\n\r\nOur learners, usually in their peer groups, collaborate on projects. Through our learner community, this is enhanced through hackathons, pitching events, and coding competitions where these teams meet industry players to test their ideas with the industry.\r\n\r\nToday, the competitive advantage is Tech skills. Technology is rapidly advancing and transforming business practices, which has inevitably inuenced how people work, and in turn, the skills that job seekers now need to adapt their skills. The Power Learn software development scholarship will enable you to become a unicorn in your industry!','Tech talent shortage  why its time to get outside your comfort zone','','publish','open','open','','tech-talent-shortage-why-its-time-to-get-outside-your-comfort-zone','','','2023-02-23 11:11:25','2023-02-23 11:11:25','',0,'http://ec2-54-241-199-161.us-west-1.compute.amazonaws.com/?p=482',0,'post','',0),(483,1,'2023-02-19 18:50:45','2023-02-19 18:50:45','','Picture1','','inherit','open','closed','','picture1','','','2023-02-19 18:50:45','2023-02-19 18:50:45','',482,'http://ec2-54-241-199-161.us-west-1.compute.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Picture1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(484,1,'2023-02-19 18:50:57','2023-02-19 18:50:57','While \"pivot,\" \"new normal,\" and \"unprecedented\" may have been some of the most annoying buzzwords to come out of the COVID-19 pandemic, theres no denying that the ability to change, move, and especially upskill is now critical in todays job market.\r\n\r\nJobs are changing more quickly than people can meet business needs. With such rapid technological movement, the World Economic Forum (WEF) projects that half of all jobs will require a change in skill sets by 2027.\r\n\r\nThe tech industry has been struggling with a skills shortage for many years. With the increasing demand for technology professionals and a limited pool of skilled workers, companies are still looking for the right talent to meet their nee