 sub-Saharan Africa. The base plan will cost $3.99 in this region, down from $7.99, and the mobile plan will cost $2.99, down from $3.99.\r\n\r\nSubscribers will pay $7.99 for the basic plan, down from $9.99, and $9.99 for the premium plan, down from $11.99.','Netflix reduces monthly subscription fees for Kenya and Sub-SaharanAfrica','','publish','open','open','','netflix-reduces-subscription','','','2023-02-22 11:28:48','2023-02-22 11:28:48','',0,'http://ec2-54-241-199-161.us-west-1.compute.amazonaws.com/?p=502',0,'post','',0),(503,1,'2023-02-22 11:25:27','2023-02-22 11:25:27','','WhatsApp Image 2023-02-22 at 07.15.37','','inherit','open','closed','','whatsapp-image-2023-02-22-at-07-15-37','','','2023-02-22 11:25:27','2023-02-22 11:25:27','',502,'http://ec2-54-241-199-161.us-west-1.compute.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/WhatsApp-Image-2023-02-22-at-07.15.37.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(504,1,'2023-02-22 11:28:48','2023-02-22 11:28:48','Netflix reduces monthly subscription fees for Kenya and Sub-SaharanAfrica\r\n\r\nThe company said in a statement on Tuesday that the price of its mobile plan would be reduced to Sh200 from Sh300 and that of its basic plan to Sh300 from Sh700. Subscribers will pay Sh700 for the basic plan, down from Sh1,100, and Sh1,100 for the premium plan, down from Sh1,450.\r\n\r\nIn a statement, Netflix stated, \"Our objective is simple: to offer a wide choice of high-quality episodes and films, chosen for you. New members who sign up will notice the higher costs right away.\r\n\r\nPrices will be reduced starting at 8 a.m. on February 21. The upgrade will be made available to current members starting with their subsequent paying cycle over the coming weeks. 30 days before the new prices are applied to them (this is just for auto-upgrades), existing members will be notified via email and within the Netflix app. The billing cycle of the particular member will determine the precise timing.\r\n\r\nMoreover, Netflix reduced its costs for customers in sub-Saharan Africa. The base plan will cost $3.99 in this region, down from $7.99, and the mobile plan will cost $2.99, down from $3.99.\r\n\r\nSubscribers will pay $7.99 for the basic plan, down from $9.99, and $9.99 for the premium plan, down from $11.99.','Netflix reduces monthly subscription fees for Kenya and Sub-SaharanAfrica','','inherit','closed','closed','','502-revision-v1','','','2023-02-22 11:28:48','2023-02-22 11:28:48','',502,'http://ec2-54-241-199-161.us-west-1.compute.amazonaws.com/?p=504',0,'revision','',0),(505,1,'2023-02-23 11:04:14','2023-02-23 11:04:14','Spotify has introduced a new feature called \"DJ\" that delivers personalized music recommendations alongside AI-generated commentary. The feature allows users to select a playlist and then receive personalized commentary about the music, as well as information about the artists and their backgrounds. The commentary is generated by Spotify\'s machine learning algorithms, which analyze data such as user listening history and preferences to create personalized commentary.\r\n\r\nSpotify\'s DJ feature is similar to a radio DJ, providing users with a curated selection of music and spoken commentary about the tracks and artists they like, using a \"stunningly realistic voice\" from Sonantic, an AI voice company acquired by Spotify in 2022. The aim is for Spotify to get to know its users so well that the DJ can choose what to play for them when they hit the button, essentially putting an \"AI DJ in your pocket.\"\r\n\r\nThe DJ feature is currently in beta testing and is only available in English for Spotify Premium subscribers in the US and Canada. The technology behind the feature is a combination of Spotify\'s existing personalization technology, the AI voice from Sonantic, and Generative AI through the use of OpenAI technology. Spotify has provided its music editors, experts, scriptwriters, and data curators with access to OpenAI\'s Generative AI tech to scale their insights about music, artists, and genres, enabling them to create culturally relevant and accurate pieces of commentary at scale.\r\n\r\nAs listeners engage with the new DJ feature, they will be presented with a personalized stream of songs that includes both newer tracks and old favorites. This stream will be continually refreshed. As they listen, they will also hear commentary directly followed by the song it\'s referring to. If the DJ misses the mark in terms of what the user wants to hear, they can tap the DJ button again to shift to a different genre, artist, or mood. The more the feature is used, the more accurate its suggestions will become.\r\n\r\nThe DJ\'s voice is based on Spotify\'s Head of Cultural Partnerships, Xavier \"X\" Jernigan, who hosted Spotify\'s morning show podcast, \"The Get Up.\" The company notes that his voice is the \"first model\" for the DJ feature, suggesting that it has plans to expand the range of voices in the future.\r\n\r\nTo access the DJ feature, users can head to the Music Feed on the Home page of Spotify\'s iOS or Android app, then tap Play on the DJ card to begin. The DJ will then begin to play a lineup of music and short commentary. In tests of the feature ahead of the launch, the voice sounded authentic even as it inserted personalized content during its introduction, like references to the names of bands the user regularly streams. However, it didn\'t immediately seem more remarkable than one of Spotify\'s personalized playlists in terms of music selection. Nevertheless, DJ\'s improvements are expected tocomeintime.','Spotify Unveils AI-Powered \'DJ\' Feature for Personalized Music ExperiencewithCommentary','','publish','open','open','','spotify-unveils-ai-powered-dj-feature','','','2023-02-23 11:04:39','2023-02-23 11:04:39','',0,'http://ec2-54-241-199-161.us-west-1.compute.amazonaws.com/?p=505',0,'post','',0),(506,1,'2023-02-23 11:04:01','2023-02-23 11:04:01','','spotify-logo-1920x1080_fouoik-1','','inherit','open','closed','','spotif